o maintain political power.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br><br>How do you know that? What, just because thousands aren't slaughtered openly you think that is not true? BTW, ever hear of Nuclear tests done in New Mexico, Nevada, the South Pacific? Oh, can you say H A N F O R D, Washington? The USA is not squeaky clean.<br><br>AND, I agree that Saddam is wrong for murdering his population, but after all, that is not for the United States alone to deal with. It is a &quot;world&quot; issue and needs to be dealt with by the coalition.<br><br><!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> &quot;2) Generally speaking the United States is on the higher end of the of the technology curve when it comes to nations of the world and we most likely have something in our own arsenal of said weapons that puts to shame most countries in the world. Why in the hell would we want to share this information with other countries and have the possiblity of someone else using our own technology against us.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br><br>Of course we wouldn't want our technology to migrate out to other nations! What makes you think other countries will happily comply with US dictates to expose their technologies? It is sheer American arrogance to think the USA is so f u c k i n g lofty with its technology that we alone ought to be making the rules (mind you as we go along!) for which all other nations should be held to!<br><br>No, Lith, I am not missing the point and you obviously refuse to see the point. If you don't feel comfortable having an international task force (UN) catalogue what biological weapons we do have, and allow them to dismantle the production facilities for those weapons, then it is hypocritical to expect that other nations should just fall over at the mere flex of US muscle and welcome the UN in to destroy their technology.<br><br>BTW, I am not defending Saddam Hussein by no means. I believe he is a threat to world peace. However, I don't think it is the role of the United States to play &quot;world cop&quot;. Especially when all that is involved is Shrub trying to get ratings because he knows jack s h i t about domestic policy. <p>Lurikeen Mali'Kyre<BR>Necromancer <BR>Proud Member of <a href="http://magustytalus.tripod.com/">The Order of Magus Tytalus</a><BR><BR>"My eyes will pierce your soul, then I will take your life!"<br></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ulithahntalon.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lith Ahntalon</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/image/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 249<br> <font color=#E9D756>(3/15/02 7:25:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=287.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Rogue state threat to world security?</span><hr size=1> 1) I never said I was a republican, so please don't put that hat on me.<br><br>2) Please name an incident where the United States used weapons of mass destruction on it's general populace as a means to maintain political power.<br><br>3) Please enlighten me on what technologies Nixon allowed authorization to sell to the USSR and China. Even if he did, this somehow justifies Clintons authorization to sell ballistic missle technology to China thus giving them a reliable vehicle to deliver nuclear warheads to U.S. shores, how?<br><br>4) Suddenly any businessman or corporation is totally ethicless, money grubbing, and just plain old greedy? For some reason being a capitalist is an evil thing?<br><br>5) If WE dismantle our bio/chem warefare arsenal, it would honestly not bother me. However, I do not see the arsenal of U.S. bio/chem weapons becoming a terrorist threat to the 